properties.locationDescription: Avalon Dam is located on the Pecos River 5 miles north of Carlsbad, New Mexico. The dam is a zoned earthfill structure that was constructed by private interests in 1888. The dam washed out in 1893 and, after reconstruction, was washed out again in 1904 by the Pecos River flood. The Reclamation Service rebuilt the dam in 1907. The height of the dam was increased in 1912, and again in 1936. The dam now has a structural height of 60 feet and a volume of 202,000 cubic yards. This is an earthfilled structure 1,360 feet long and 53 feet high. There are three spillways and an outlet works. The original reservoir storage capacity was 7,000 acre-feet; a 1996 resurvey showed a capacity of 4,466 acre-feet at the top of conservation pool.

properties.locationDescription: Heron Dam is located on Willow Creek just above the point where Willow Creek enters the Rio Chama. The dam is an earthfill structure 269 feet high which forms a reservoir with a capacity of 401,320 acre-feet and a surface area of 5,950 acres. The spillway has a capacity of 660 cubic feet per second, and the outlet works has a capacity of 4,160 cubic feet per second Storage from Heron Dam provides water for municipal, domestic, industrial, recreation, and fish and wildlife purposes and provides supplemental water for irrigation. Heron Reservoir is operated by Reclamation in compliance with applicable federal and state laws, including the San Juan-Chama Project authorization and the Rio Grande and Colorado compacts. Under these laws, only imported San Juan-Chama Project water may be stored in Heron Reservoir; there are no provisions for storing native Rio Grande water. Thus, all native Rio Grande water is released to the river below Heron Dam. The outlet works for El Vado Dam, located 6 miles downstream of Heron Dam, were enlarged in 1965-1966 so that San Juan-Chama Project releases from Heron Reservoir could be passed unimpeded through El Vado Reservoir. The capacity of the outlet works is 6,600 cubic feet per second.

Water released from Shasta Dam downstream to the Keswick Reservoir is stored for release through Keswick Dam and Powerplant. properties.name: Bumping Lake and Bumping Lake Dam (BUM)

properties.locationDescription: Deadwood Dam is located in west-central Idaho on the Deadwood River about 25 miles above its confluence with the South Fork of the Payette River and about 90 miles above Black Canyon Diversion Dam. The damsite is located in a narrow canyon where the Deadwood River has cut into granite bedrock, approximately 53 miles northeast of Boise, Idaho. The dam lies on the western slope of the Sawtooth Mountains. Deadwood Dam is a concrete-arch structure, was completed in 1931, and provides a regulated flow for the powerplant at Black Canyon Diversion Dam and for irrigation in the Payette Division and Emmett Irrigation District.
properties.name: Deadwood Reservoir and Dam

properties.locationName: Henry Hagg Lake and Scoggins Dam (SCO)
properties.locationDescription: Scoggins Dam is a 151-foot-high zoned earthfill structure and was completed in 1975. Scoggins Dam and Henry Hagg Lake are located along Scoggins Creek approximately 6 miles southwest of Forest Grove, Oregon. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = SCO.
properties.name: Henry Hagg Lake and Scoggins Dam (SCO)

properties.locationDescription: Como Dam was completed in 1910 by local irrigators and rehabilitated on its crest and upstream face by the Bureau of Reclamation in 1954. This semi hydraulic earthfill dam is at the end of a natural lake. The dam and reservoir are along Rock Creek and are located approximately 60 miles southwest of Missoula, Montana. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = CMO.
properties.name: Lake Como and Como Dam (CMO)

properties.locationDescription: Lake Waha, located on Lake Creek, is a natural lake that also serves as off stream storage for the Lewiston Orchards Project. The lake is located about one mile southwest of the village of Waha and about 19 miles southeast of Lewiston, Idaho. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = WAH.
properties.name: Lake Waha (WAH)

properties.locationDescription: Mann Creek Dam, on Mann Creek about 13 miles northeast of Weiser, Idaho, is a zoned earth and rockfill structure. The dam was completed in 1967. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = MAN.
properties.name: Mann Creek Reservoir and Dam (MAN)

properties.locationDescription: McKay Dam is located on McKay Creek about 6 miles south of Pendleton, Oregon. It was constructed to furnish a supplementary supply of water to Stanfield and Westland Irrigation Districts. The dam is an earthfill structure with a reinforced concrete paved upstream slope and was completed in 1927. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = MCK.
properties.name: McKay Reservoir and Dam (MCK)

properties.locationDescription: Ochoco Dam, a hydraulic-fill structure on Ochoco Creek 6 miles east of Prineville, Oregon, was constructed immediately after World War I as a part of the Veterans Farm Settlement Program undertaken by the State of Oregon. It was completed in 1920. The dam provides flood control of Ochoco Creek in addition to storing water for irrigation. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = OCH.
properties.name: Ochoco Reservoir and Dam (OCH)

properties.locationName: Prineville Reservoir and Arthur R. Bowman Dam (PRV)
properties.locationDescription: Arthur R. Bowman Dam (formerly Prineville Dam) is an earthfill structure on the Crooked River about 20 miles upstream from Prineville. The dam was completed in 1961. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = PRV.
properties.name: Prineville Reservoir and Arthur R. Bowman Dam (PRV)

properties.locationDescription: Thief Valley Dam is a reinforced concrete, slab and buttress (Ambursen) structure, 73 feet high and 390 feet long. It was completed in 1932 and is located approximately 16 miles north of Baker City, Oregon. The dam and reservoir are along the Powder River. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = THF.
properties.name: Thief Valley Reservoir and Dam (THF)

properties.locationName: Tom Steed Reservoir and Mountain Park Dam
properties.locationDescription: Mountain Park Dam forms Tom Steed Reservoir and regulates natural flows of West Otter Creek and diverted flows from Elk Creek to provide municipal and industrial water supplies for the cities of Altus, Snyder, and Frederick, Oklahoma. The water is conveyed from the reservoir to the project cities through an aqueduct system that consists of 40 miles of pipeline, two pumping plants, a chlorination station, and other appurtenant facilities. Mountain Park Dam and Tom Steed Reservoir are owned by the Bureau of Reclamation and operated by Mountain Park Master Conservancy District.
properties.name: Tom Steed Reservoir and Mountain Park Dam

properties.locationDescription: Unity Dam, located about 40 miles southwest of Baker City, Oregon, is a rolled, zoned earthfill-type structure, 82 feet high above its foundation. The dam is along the Burnt River and was completed in 1938. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = UNY.
properties.name: Unity Reservoir and Dam (UNY)

properties.locationDescription: Warm Springs Dam is on the Middle Fork of the Malheur River about 13 miles southwest of Juntura, Oregon. The dam, constructed by the Warmsprings Irrigation District, is a 106-foot-high thin arch structure and was completed in 1919. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = WAR.
properties.name: Warm Springs Reservoir and Dam (WAR)

properties.locationDescription: Crawford Dam is on Iron Creek, a tributary of the Smith Fork about 1 mile south of Crawford, Colorado. The Crawford Reservoir regulates flows of Iron Creek and its tributaries as well as the surplus flows of the Smith Fork of the Gunnison River, diverted to the reservoir by the feeder canal. Small quantities of reservoir storage water are released to Iron Creek and diverted by several small private ditches. The remainder is released to Aspen Canal for conveyance to private ditches for distribution. Some of the storage releases through Aspen Canal replace former direct flow diversions from Smith Fork, permitting additional direct flow diversions for project land higher on the stream. Crawford Dam is an earthfill structure 162 feet high and 580 feet long, with a volume of 1,006,000 cubic yards. The uncontrolled overflow spillway is in the left abutment of the dam and has a capacity of 1,400 cubic feet per second. The outlet works in the right abutment of the dam carries water through a 34-inch-diameter steel pipe controlled by four 2.25-foot-square high-pressure gates. Maximum discharge capacity to Aspen Canal is 125 cubic feet per second. Crawford Reservoir has a total capacity of 14,395 acre-feet and an active capacity of 14,064 acre-feet.
properties.name: Crawford Dam and Reservoir

properties.locationDescription: The Elwha River is a 45-mile (72 km) river on the Olympic Peninsula in the U.S. state of Washington. From its source at Elwha snowfinger in the Olympic Mountains, it flows generally north to the Strait of Juan de Fuca. Most of the river's course is within the Olympic National Park. From 1911 to 2014, dams blocked fish passage on the lower Elwha River. The National Park Service removed the two dams as part of the Elwha Ecosystem Restoration Project. Dam removal work began in September 2011 and was completed in August 2014.
properties.name: Elwha River

properties.name: Agate Reservoir and Dam (AGA)

properties.name: American Falls Reservoir and Dam (AMF)

properties.locationName: Billy Clapp Lake and Pinto Dam (BCP)
properties.locationDescription: Pinto Dam is located in the eastern portion of Grant County in Washington. The dam was constructed from 1946 to 1948. Pinto Dam forms Billy Clapp Lake, an off-stream reservoir which stores water for the Columbia Basin Irrigation Project. The nearest towns are Stratford, Washington and Wilson Creek, Washington. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = BCP.
properties.name: Billy Clapp Lake and Pinto Dam (BCP)

properties.locationName: Conconully Lake and Salmon Lake Dam (CCL)
properties.locationDescription: Salmon Lake Dam is an earthfill structure 54 feet high. The dam was completed in 1921 and is upstream of Conconully Dam in Conconully, Washington. Conconully Lake provides instream storage along the North Fork Salmon Creek. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = CCL.
properties.name: Conconully Lake and Salmon Lake Dam (CCL)

properties.locationDescription: Cle Elum Dam, on the Cle Elum River 10 miles northwest of Cle Elum, Washington, is an earthfill dam constructed at the end of a natural lake that forms a reservoir. The dam was constructed from 1931 to 1933. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = CLE.
properties.name: Cle Elum Lake and Dam (CLE)

properties.locationDescription: Cold Springs Dam is a zoned earthfill type dam and was completed in 1908. Cold Springs Reservoir is located offstream about 6 miles northeast of Hermiston, Oregon. Water is diverted to the reservoir from the Umatilla River by the Feed Canal Diversion Dam and Canal. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = CLS.
properties.name: Cold Springs Reservoir and Dam (CLS)

properties.locationDescription: Crane Prairie Dam is an earthfill structure and was constructed from 1939 to 1940. Crane Prairie Reservoir and Dam are located about 2 miles above Wickiup Reservoir on the Deschutes River and approximately 35 miles southwest of Bend, Oregon. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = CRA.
properties.name: Crane Prairie Reservoir and Dam (CRA)

properties.locationName: Crescent Lake and Crescent Lake Dam (CRE)
properties.locationDescription: Crescent Lake and Crescent Lake Dam are located in the Deschutes National Forest approximately 60 miles southwest of Bend, Oregon. The dam was completed in 1956. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = CRE.
properties.name: Crescent Lake and Crescent Lake Dam (CRE)

properties.locationDescription: Emigrant Dam and Lake are located 7.5 miles southeast of Ashland, Oregon on Emigrant Creek. The dam was constructed in 1924 and had modified construction from 1958 to1961. There are three dikes on Emigrant Lake in addition to the dam. The reservoir regulates Green Springs Powerplant discharges and provides additional storage for irrigation. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = EMI.
properties.name: Emigrant Lake and Dam (EMI)

properties.locationName: Black Canyon Reservoir, Diversion Dam, and Powerplant (EMM)
properties.locationDescription: Black Canyon Diversion Dam, on the Payette River near Emmett, Idaho, is a concrete gravity type dam with an ogee overflow spillway and was originally constructed from 1922 to 1924. The dam serves to divert water to the Payette Division through Black Canyon Canal. The two unit powerplant supplies power to irrigation loads in the Boise, Owyhee, and Minidoka Projects as part of Reclamation's Southern Idaho Power System. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = EMM.
properties.name: Black Canyon Reservoir, Diversion Dam, and Powerplant (EMM)

properties.locationName: Fish Lake and Fish Lake Dam (FIS)
properties.locationDescription: Fish Lake Dam, located 35 miles northeast of Medford, Oregon on the North Fork of Little Butte Creek, is an earth and rockfill structure. The dam was originally constructed from 1902 to 1908. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = FIS.
properties.name: Fish Lake and Fish Lake Dam (FIS)

properties.locationName: Fourmile Lake and Fourmile Lake Dam (FOR)
properties.locationDescription: Fourmile Lake Dam, located 45 miles northeast of Medford, Oregon on Fourmile Creek, is a rockfill structure. The dam was completed in 1922. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = FOR.
properties.name: Fourmile Lake and Fourmile Lake Dam (FOR)

properties.locationName: Grassy Lake and Grassy Lake Dam (GRS)
properties.locationDescription: Grassy Lake Dam is a zoned earthfill storage dam on Grassy Creek in Wyoming near the southern boundary of Yellowstone National Park. The reservoir's storage capacity supplements the storage at Island Park Reservoir. Grassy Lake Dam was constructed from 1937 to 1939. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = GRS.
properties.name: Grassy Lake and Grassy Lake Dam (GRS)

properties.locationDescription: Haystack Dam is a zoned earthfill offstream storage facility located about 10 miles south of Madras, Oregon. Most of the stored water in the reservoir is diverted from the North Unit Main Canal which receives its water from Wickiup Reservoir. Haystack Dam was constructed from 1956 1957. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = HAY.
properties.name: Haystack Reservoir and Dam (HAY)

properties.locationName: Henrys Lake and Henrys Lake Dam (HEN)
properties.locationDescription: Henrys Lake and Henrys Lake Dam are located in northeastern Idaho. The lake provides the headwaters of the Henrys Fork, a tributary of the Snake River. The dam is approximately 17 miles west of the western boundary of Yellowstone National Park. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = HEN.
properties.name: Henrys Lake and Henrys Lake Dam (HEN)

properties.locationName: Hungry Horse Reservoir, Dam, and Powerplant (HGH)
properties.locationDescription: Hungry Horse Dam is 564 feet high and has a variable-thickness concrete arch structure. The spillway is the highest morning-glory structure in the world. Hungry Horse Dam and Powerplant are located approximately 9 miles southeast of Columbia Falls, Montana and are on the South Fork of the Flathead River. The principal power benefit from the powerplant arises from its ability to store water through the spring flood season for later release. Hungry Horse Dam was constructed from 1948 to 1953. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = HGH.
properties.name: Hungry Horse Reservoir, Dam, and Powerplant (HGH)

properties.locationDescription: Howard Prairie Dam is a zoned earthfill structure and was constructed from 1957 to 1958. The dam is on Beaver Creek, 18 miles east of Ashland, Oregon. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = HPD.
properties.name: Howard Prairie Lake and Dam (HPD)

properties.locationDescription: Hyatt Dam is on Keene Creek, east of the Cascade Divide approximately 27 miles southeast of Talent, Oregon. It is an earth and rockfill structure. Hyatt Dam was constructed by the Talent Irrigation District in the early 1920s for irrigation storage. In 1960, the Bureau of Reclamation rehabilitated the dam, constructing fish screens and recreation facilities as a part of the Talent Division. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = HYA.
properties.name: Hyatt Reservoir and Dam (HYA)

properties.locationDescription: Island Park Dam is located 38 miles north of Ashton, Idaho, on Henrys Fork. The dam is a zoned earthfill structure and was constructed from 1937 to 1939. Water stored at Island Park Reservoir is used in Fremont and Madison Counties in northeastern Idaho.  Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = ISL.
properties.name: Island Park Reservoir and Dam (ISL)

properties.locationName: Jackson Lake and Jackson Lake Dam (JCK)
properties.locationDescription: Jackson Lake Dam is a concrete gravity and zoned embankment dam on the Snake River. The dam was originally constructed in 1912 and had modified construction in 1916 and from 1986 to 1988. The dam is located in Grand Teton National Park in Wyoming. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = JCK.
properties.name: Jackson Lake and Jackson Lake Dam (JCK)

properties.locationDescription: Kachess Dam is an earthfill structure located on the Kachess River about 2 miles northwest of Easton, Washington. This dam was built at the lower end of a natural lake and created a reservoir over a natural lake. The dam was constructed from 1910 to 1912. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = KAC.
properties.name: Kachess Lake and Dam (KAC)

properties.locationDescription: Keechelus Dam was constructed at the lower end of a natural lake and is on the Yakima River, 10 miles northwest of Easton, Washington. This earthfill structure was completed in 1917. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = KEE.
properties.name: Keechelus Lake and Dam (KEE)

properties.locationName: Lake Lowell and Deer Flat Dams (LOW)
properties.locationDescription: Lake Lowell, originally known as Deer Flat Reservoir, is an offstream reservoir formed by three earthfill dams enclosing a natural depression southwest of Nampa, Idaho. These three dams are the Upper, Middle (Forest Dam), and Lower Embankments. A fourth embankment called the East (Roadway Dike) is to protect farmsteads on the eastern end of the reservoir when the reservoir is full. The dams were constructed from 1906 to 1911. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = LOW.
properties.name: Lake Lowell and Deer Flat Dams (LOW)

properties.locationDescription: Lucky Peak Dam provides flood risk management, fish and wildlife habitat, irrigation and recreation. The dam is a rolled earthfill dam. Lucky Peak Dam and Lake are located in Boise, Idaho downstream from Arrowrock Dam and Reservoir. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = LUC.
properties.name: Lucky Peak Lake and Dam (LUC)

properties.locationDescription: Milner Dam is located on the Snake River near Milner, Idaho. The dam is downstream from Minidoka Dam and Lake Walcott. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = MIL.
properties.name: Milner Lake and Dam (MIL)

properties.locationName: Lake Walcott, Minidoka Dam, and Minidoka Powerplant (MIN)
properties.locationDescription: Minidoka Powerplant and Dam is a combined diversion, storage, and power structure located just south of Minidoka, Idaho. Minidoka Dam was originally designed and constructed without a powerplant and was completed in 1907. The powerplant (and three pumping plants) was added later (1909-1910) to allow water to be delivered to lands which could not be fed by gravity irrigation. Lake Walcott and Minidoka Dam are on the Snake River. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = MIN.
properties.name: Lake Walcott, Minidoka Dam, and Minidoka Powerplant (MIN)

properties.locationDescription: Owyhee Dam is a concrete, thick-arch structure. At the time of its construction, Owyhee ranked as the world's highest dam. It was constructed from 1928 to 1932. Lake Owyhee and Owyhee Dam are located on the Owyhee River approximately 30 miles southwest of Ontario, Oregon. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = OWY.
properties.name: Lake Owyhee and Owyhee Dam (OWY)

properties.locationDescription: Palisades Dam is located on the Snake River about 55 miles southeast of Idaho Falls, Idaho. It is a large zoned earthfill structure and was constructed from 1951 to 1957. Palisades Powerplant serves large irrigation pumping power requirements on and near the Minidoka Project in southern Idaho. The powerplant is on the downstream toe of the dam on the west side of the river and has four units. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = PAL.
properties.name: Palisades Reservoir, Dam, and Powerplant (PAL)

properties.locationName: Payette Lake and Payette Lake Dam (PAY)
properties.locationDescription: Payette Lake is located in McCall, Idaho. It is situated on the North Fork Payette River, which feeds into the downstream Lake Cascade. Columbia Basin Teletype (CBTT) = PAY.

properties.name: Phillips Lake and Mason Dam (PHL)
